## Type 1.3 — DOM-Based XSS

### How it works
Script never hits the server — it's injected and executed **entirely in the browser** via unsafe DOM manipulation.

```
Page JS reads window.location.hash and writes it to innerHTML:
document.getElementById('msg').innerHTML = window.location.hash.slice(1);

Attacker sends:
https://yourapp.com/page#<img src=x onerror=alert(document.cookie)>

→ No server involved — runs directly in browser
```

### Real exploit patterns
```js
// ❌ Dangerous sinks — DOM-based XSS entry points
element.innerHTML = userInput;
element.outerHTML = userInput;
document.write(userInput);
document.writeln(userInput);
eval(userInput);
setTimeout(userInput, 100);     // string form of setTimeout
new Function(userInput)();
location.href = userInput;      // if userInput is javascript:...
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Safe DOM APIs — use these instead
element.textContent = userInput;       // never executes as HTML
element.setAttribute('data-val', userInput);

// ✅ For URLs — validate protocol
function safeRedirect(url) {
  const parsed = new URL(url);
  if (!['http:', 'https:'].includes(parsed.protocol)) {
    throw new Error('Unsafe URL protocol');
  }
  window.location.href = url;
}

// ✅ Never pass user input to eval, setTimeout string, or new Function
// ✅ Use DOMPurify if innerHTML is unavoidable
```

---

## Type 1.4 — Mutation XSS (mXSS)

### How it works
You sanitize HTML → pass it to innerHTML → the browser's HTML parser **mutates** it during parsing into something that executes scripts. The sanitizer saw clean HTML, the browser sees different HTML.

```html
<!-- Input after sanitization (looks safe) -->
<p id="test"><svg><![CDATA[</p><script>alert(1)</script>]]></svg></p>

<!-- After browser parses it (mutated) -->
<p id="test"><svg></svg></p><script>alert(1)</script><p></p>
<!-- Script executes! -->
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Use DOMPurify — it's specifically built to handle mXSS
// It serializes and re-parses multiple times to catch mutations

import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';

// Enable mXSS protection explicitly
const clean = DOMPurify.sanitize(html, {
  RETURN_DOM: false,
  FORCE_BODY: true,    // forces into body context, prevents namespace confusion
});
```

---

## XSS — Master Protection Checklist

```
Code level:
  ✅ Use JSX rendering — never innerHTML with user data
  ✅ DOMPurify.sanitize() for any HTML rendering
  ✅ Validate URL protocols before href/src assignment
  ✅ Never use eval(), new Function(), setTimeout(string)
  ✅ Sanitize on backend BEFORE storing in DB

HTTP Headers:
  ✅ Content-Security-Policy: script-src 'self'
  ✅ X-XSS-Protection: 1; mode=block (legacy browsers)

Tooling:
  ✅ eslint-plugin-react: 'react/no-danger' rule = error
  ✅ DOMPurify for all rich text rendering
```

