# ATTACK 2 — CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery)

## What is it?
Attacker tricks an **already-authenticated** user's browser into making an unintended request to your server.  
The browser automatically sends cookies with every request — the server thinks it's legitimate.

**Goal:** Transfer money, change email/password, delete account, post content — anything the user can do.

---

## Type 2.1 — GET-Based CSRF

### How it works
Attacker embeds a GET request in an image tag on their site.  
When victim visits attacker's page, browser fires the request with victim's cookies.

```html
<!-- Attacker's page -->
<img src="https://yourbank.com/transfer?to=attacker&amount=10000" style="display:none">

<!-- Victim visits attacker's page → browser GETs that URL with victim's bank cookies
   → transfer executes if the bank uses GET for transfers (bad design) -->
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Never use GET for state-changing operations
// GET = read only. POST/PUT/DELETE = mutations.

// ❌ Bad API design
app.get('/api/transfer', transferHandler);   // CSRF-able

// ✅ Correct
app.post('/api/transfer', authenticate, csrfProtection, transferHandler);
```

---

## Type 2.2 — POST-Based CSRF

### How it works
Attacker creates a hidden auto-submitting form on their site.  
When victim visits, form submits instantly with victim's cookies.

```html
<!-- Attacker's page — auto-submits on load -->
<form id="csrf-form" action="https://yourapp.com/api/change-email" method="POST">
  <input type="hidden" name="email" value="attacker@evil.com">
</form>
<script>document.getElementById('csrf-form').submit();</script>

<!-- Victim's browser submits this form with their session cookie
   → Email changed to attacker's email → account takeover -->
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ CSRF Token pattern

// Backend — generate and send token
const csrf = require('csurf');
const csrfProtection = csrf({ cookie: { httpOnly: false, secure: true, sameSite: 'strict' } });

app.get('/api/csrf-token', csrfProtection, (req, res) => {
  res.json({ csrfToken: req.csrfToken() });
});

// Frontend — include in every mutation
const { data } = await axios.get('/api/csrf-token');
const csrfToken = data.csrfToken;

await fetch('/api/change-email', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
    'X-CSRF-Token': csrfToken  // attacker can't get this — same-origin only
  },
  body: JSON.stringify({ email: newEmail })
});

// Backend — validate token on every POST/PUT/DELETE
// csurf middleware does this automatically
app.post('/api/change-email', authenticate, csrfProtection, changeEmailHandler);
```

---

## Type 2.3 — JSON-Based CSRF

### How it works
Modern APIs accept `Content-Type: application/json`.  
Older belief: "JSON POST can't be forged cross-origin." This was wrong — Flash could do it, and some parsers accept `text/plain` with JSON body.

```html
<!-- Attacker's page -->
<script>
  fetch('https://yourapp.com/api/transfer', {
    method: 'POST',
    credentials: 'include',           // sends victim's cookies!
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' },
    body: '{"to":"attacker","amount":5000}'
  });
</script>
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Check Content-Type strictly on the server
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (['POST', 'PUT', 'PATCH', 'DELETE'].includes(req.method)) {
    if (!req.headers['content-type']?.includes('application/json')) {
      return res.status(415).json({ error: 'Unsupported Media Type' });
    }
  }
  next();
});

// ✅ SameSite cookie flag — most effective modern defense
res.cookie('session', token, {
  sameSite: 'strict',  // browser won't send cookie on cross-origin requests
  httpOnly: true,
  secure: true
});
```

---

## CSRF — Master Protection Checklist

```
  ✅ SameSite=Strict on all session cookies (primary defense)
  ✅ CSRF token for all state-changing endpoints
  ✅ CORS whitelist — only your domains allowed
  ✅ Verify Content-Type: application/json on APIs
  ✅ Never use GET for mutations
  ✅ Custom request header (X-Requested-With: XMLHttpRequest)
     — cross-origin requests can't set custom headers
```

