# ATTACK 3 — SQL Injection

## What is it?
Attacker manipulates database queries by injecting SQL code into user inputs.  
If your query is built by string concatenation, attacker controls the SQL itself.

**Goal:** Dump entire database, bypass authentication, delete data, gain admin access.

---

## Type 3.1 — Classic SQL Injection

### How it works
```sql
-- Your query (vulnerable)
SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '[user input]' AND password = '[user input]'

-- Attacker enters as email:
' OR '1'='1' --

-- Resulting query:
SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '' OR '1'='1' --' AND password = '...'
-- The -- comments out the password check
-- '1'='1' is always true → returns ALL users → logged in as first user (admin)
```

### Protection
```js
// ❌ String concatenation — NEVER
const query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '${email}'`;

// ✅ Parameterized query — ALWAYS
const result = await pool.query(
  'SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1 AND password_hash = $2',
  [email, passwordHash]
);
// pg driver sends params separately — SQL structure can't be altered
```

---

## Type 3.2 — Union-Based SQL Injection

### How it works
Attacker uses UNION to append results from other tables to the original query.

```sql
-- Vulnerable search query
SELECT id, name, price FROM products WHERE name = '[input]'

-- Attacker enters:
' UNION SELECT username, password, email FROM users --

-- Resulting query:
SELECT id, name, price FROM products WHERE name = ''
UNION SELECT username, password, email FROM users --'

-- Returns all usernames and password hashes alongside products!
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Parameterized queries prevent this entirely
// ✅ Principle of least privilege — DB user only has SELECT on products table
//    Cannot select from users table even if injection occurs

// PostgreSQL — create restricted DB user
// CREATE USER app_user WITH PASSWORD 'secret';
// GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE ON products TO app_user;
// No access to users table at all
```

---

## Type 3.3 — Blind SQL Injection

### How it works
App doesn't show DB errors — attacker infers data by asking true/false questions.

```sql
-- Boolean-based blind
-- Attacker: does the first letter of admin password start with 'a'?
https://yourapp.com/user?id=1 AND SUBSTRING(password,1,1)='a'

-- If page loads normally → TRUE → first char is 'a'
-- If page errors/changes → FALSE → try next char

-- Time-based blind (when no visual difference)
-- PostgreSQL
id=1; SELECT CASE WHEN (1=1) THEN pg_sleep(5) ELSE pg_sleep(0) END --
-- If page takes 5 seconds → condition was TRUE → data confirmed
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Parameterized queries — same fix
// ✅ Never expose DB errors to users
// ✅ Consistent response times (hard — but WAF helps)
// ✅ Web Application Firewall detects sequential probing patterns

// Express — never send raw DB errors
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // log internally
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Something went wrong' }); // generic to user
});
```

---

## Type 3.4 — Second-Order SQL Injection

### How it works
Payload is stored safely in DB first, then used unsafely in a later query.

```
Step 1: Attacker registers with username: admin'--
        → Stored safely in DB (parameterized INSERT)

Step 2: App later does:
        UPDATE users SET password = '[new]' WHERE username = 'admin'--'
        → Built with string concat using the stored username
        → Updates admin's password instead of attacker's!
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Use parameterized queries EVERYWHERE — not just on input, but when reading from DB too
// ✅ Never trust data just because it came from your own database

// Both these must be parameterized:
// When storing:
await pool.query('INSERT INTO users (username) VALUES ($1)', [username]);

// When using stored value later:
await pool.query(
  'UPDATE users SET password_hash = $1 WHERE username = $2',
  [newHash, storedUsername]  // storedUsername from DB — still parameterized!
);
```

---

## SQL Injection — Master Protection Checklist

```
  ✅ Parameterized queries / prepared statements — EVERYWHERE
  ✅ ORM (Prisma, TypeORM) — uses parameterized queries by default
  ✅ Stored procedures (also parameterized)
  ✅ Principle of least privilege — DB user has only needed permissions
  ✅ Never expose raw DB errors to users
  ✅ Input validation — whitelist allowed characters where possible
  ✅ WAF rules to detect SQL patterns
```

