# ATTACK 5 — MITM (Man-in-the-Middle)

## What is it?
Attacker positions themselves between user and server — intercepts and reads (or modifies) all traffic.  
Common on public WiFi (coffee shops, airports).

```
Victim  →  [Attacker intercepts]  →  Your Server
                    ↓
        Reads tokens, modifies responses,
        injects scripts, captures passwords
```

## Types

### Type 5.1 — HTTP Interception
Site uses HTTP → all traffic is plaintext → attacker reads everything.

### Type 5.2 — SSL Stripping
Attacker downgrades HTTPS connection to HTTP even if your server supports HTTPS.

```
Victim requests: https://yourapp.com
Attacker intercepts, requests https:// themselves, serves http:// to victim
Victim sees http:// — all traffic now readable
```

### Type 5.3 — Fake WiFi Hotspot
Attacker creates "Free Airport WiFi" network → all traffic routes through them.

### Protection
```js
// ✅ HTTPS everywhere — TLS 1.2+ only
// Nginx:
ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
ssl_ciphers HIGH:!aNULL:!MD5:!RC4;

// ✅ HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS)
// Browser remembers to ALWAYS use HTTPS — SSL stripping impossible
add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload";
// After first visit, browser refuses to connect over HTTP — ever

// ✅ Submit to HSTS Preload List
// https://hstspreload.org → browser hardcodes your domain as HTTPS-only
// Even first visit is HTTPS — zero window for SSL stripping

// ✅ In Node — redirect HTTP to HTTPS
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (req.headers['x-forwarded-proto'] !== 'https') {
    return res.redirect(301, `https://${req.hostname}${req.originalUrl}`);
  }
  next();
});

// ✅ Certificate Pinning (mobile apps)
// App only accepts your specific SSL certificate — fake certs rejected
```

