# ATTACK 6 — Broken Authentication

## What is it?
Weak auth implementation that lets attackers take over accounts without knowing the password.

## Types

### Type 6.1 — Credential Stuffing
Attacker uses breached username/password lists from other sites — tests them on your app.  
Works because users reuse passwords.

```
Attacker has 1M leaked credentials from LinkedIn breach
Fires them all at your /login endpoint
1-2% hit rate = thousands of compromised accounts
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Rate limiting on login
const authLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,
  max: 5,
  skipSuccessfulRequests: true
});
app.post('/api/auth/login', authLimiter, loginHandler);

// ✅ Account lockout after N failures
let failedAttempts = {}; // use Redis in production

async function loginHandler(req, res) {
  const key = req.ip + req.body.email;

  if (failedAttempts[key] >= 5) {
    return res.status(429).json({ error: 'Account temporarily locked' });
  }

  const valid = await verifyCredentials(req.body);
  if (!valid) {
    failedAttempts[key] = (failedAttempts[key] || 0) + 1;
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });
  }

  failedAttempts[key] = 0;
  // issue token...
}

// ✅ MFA — second factor defeats credential stuffing entirely
// ✅ Have I Been Pwned API — warn users if their password was breached
const { pwnedPassword } = require('hibp');
const count = await pwnedPassword(password);
if (count > 0) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: 'This password was found in a data breach. Choose another.' });
}
```

### Type 6.2 — Brute Force
Attacker systematically tries every possible password combination.

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Rate limiting (same as above)
// ✅ CAPTCHA after N failed attempts
// ✅ bcrypt with high cost factor — each guess takes 100ms+
const hash = await bcrypt.hash(password, 12); // 2^12 rounds
// At 12 rounds: ~300ms to hash — brute force at scale becomes infeasible

// ✅ Exponential backoff — lockout duration increases with attempts
function getLockoutDuration(attempts) {
  if (attempts < 5) return 0;
  if (attempts < 10) return 60 * 1000;        // 1 minute
  if (attempts < 20) return 15 * 60 * 1000;   // 15 minutes
  return 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000;                 // 24 hours
}
```

### Type 6.3 — Session Fixation
Attacker sets a known session ID before login — after victim logs in, attacker uses same session ID.

```
1. Attacker gets session ID: sess=abc123
2. Attacker tricks victim: https://yourapp.com/login?sessionid=abc123
3. Victim logs in → server associates sess=abc123 with victim's account
4. Attacker uses sess=abc123 → logged in as victim!
```

### Protection
```js
// ✅ Regenerate session ID after login — always
app.post('/api/auth/login', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await verifyCredentials(req.body);
  if (!user) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });

  // Destroy old session, create new one
  req.session.regenerate((err) => {
    req.session.userId = user.id;
    req.session.role = user.role;
    res.json({ success: true });
  });
});
```

