# ATTACK 7 — Sensitive Data Exposure

## What is it?
Sensitive information is accidentally exposed — in API responses, browser storage, URLs, logs, or source code.

## Types

### Type 7.1 — Over-Fetching API Data
```js
// ❌ Returns entire user object including hash, internal flags, etc.
app.get('/api/profile', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1', [req.user.id]);
  res.json(user.rows[0]);
  // Sends: { id, email, password_hash, is_admin, internal_notes, created_at, ... }
});

// ✅ Return only what's needed
app.get('/api/profile', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.query(
    'SELECT id, name, email, avatar_url, created_at FROM users WHERE id = $1',
    [req.user.id]
  );
  res.json(user.rows[0]);
});
```

### Type 7.2 — Sensitive Data in URLs
```
❌ https://yourapp.com/reset-password?token=abc123&email=user@mail.com
   → URL appears in browser history, server logs, Referer headers

✅ POST request with token in body
✅ Short-lived one-time tokens, expired immediately after use
```

### Type 7.3 — Secrets in Frontend Bundle
```js
// ❌ In any React component or utility file
const STRIPE_SECRET = 'sk_live_xxxx';  // bundled and visible to anyone
const DB_PASSWORD = 'supersecret';

// ✅ Only non-sensitive config in frontend
const STRIPE_PK = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PK; // publishable key only
// Secret key stays server-side only
```

### Type 7.4 — console.log in Production
```js
// ❌
console.log('User data:', user);       // contains PII
console.log('Token:', accessToken);   // logs sensitive token

// ✅ Remove all console.logs in production
// Use a logger like Winston with log levels
const logger = require('winston');

// Only logs in development
logger.debug('User logged in', { userId: user.id });  // no PII in logs

// ESLint rule to catch this:
"no-console": ["error", { allow: ["warn", "error"] }]
```

