# ATTACK 11 — Subdomain Takeover

## What is it?
Company sets up `api.yourapp.com` pointing to a cloud service (Heroku, S3, GitHub Pages).  
Service is deleted but DNS record remains — attacker claims that service and now controls `api.yourapp.com`.

```
DNS: api.yourapp.com → CNAME → yourapp.herokuapp.com
Company deletes Heroku app → yourapp.herokuapp.com is unclaimed
Attacker creates Heroku app with name "yourapp" → controls api.yourapp.com!

Now attacker can:
→ Serve malicious scripts from api.yourapp.com (same origin as app)
→ Set cookies for .yourapp.com domain
→ Steal tokens, conduct phishing
```

### Protection
```bash
# ✅ Audit all DNS records regularly
# Tool: subjack, nuclei, or manually check CNAME targets

# Check if a CNAME target is still claimed:
dig api.yourapp.com CNAME
curl https://yourapp.herokuapp.com  # still yours?

# ✅ Delete DNS records BEFORE decommissioning services
# ✅ Use dangling DNS scanner in CI

# GitHub Action — subdomain takeover scanner
- uses: actions/checkout@v3
- run: npx subjack -w subdomains.txt -t 20 -o results.txt
```

