# Interview Closing Answer

> *"Frontend attacks fall into a few categories — XSS exploits the DOM and trust the browser places in scripts, CSRF exploits the browser's automatic cookie sending, SQL injection exploits string-concatenated queries, and there are deeper attacks like prototype pollution, clickjacking, and supply chain compromises. My defense approach is layered: React's JSX handles basic XSS automatically, DOMPurify covers rich text, SameSite cookies + CSRF tokens cover request forgery, parameterized queries eliminate injection entirely, and Helmet sets the HTTP headers that prevent clickjacking and enforce HTTPS. The mindset is — every piece of user input is hostile until proven otherwise."*
